ADA Project- Weapon carrying and victims of bullying

Nkiru Obi

11/3/2021

I used Youth Risk Behavioral Surveillance (YRBS) 2019 data compiled by the CDC.

Data source:

  • https://www.cdc.gov/healthyyouth/data/yrbs/files/2019/XXH2019_YRBS_Data.dat

Sample characteristics

  • collected in 2019.
  • sample size= 13677.
  • 6 variables: all factor variables

Research question

  • HOW DID WEAPON CARRYING IN SCHOOL DIFFER BETWEEN BULLIED AND NONBULLIED HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS IN THE UNITED STATES IN 2019.

Logistic regression purpose

  • Logistic regression was used to predict the probability of the outcome variable, weapon carrying to school.
  • In this case, we are determining whether the predictor variable- victimization help predict weapon carrying to school.
  • The outcome variable, weapon carrying, is a categorical variable recoded with 2 categories (binary variable): did not carry weapon (0) and carried weapon (1).
  • Because outcome is binary, the model predicts probability of being in one of the two categories.
  • I would be adjusting for age, sex, grade, and sexual identity as confounders as identified by Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG).

Codebook:

  • Q1= age- factor variable with 5 levels (12 years old or younger, 13 years old, 14 years old, 15 years old, 16 years old, 17 years old, 18 years old and older).This is recoded as 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, and 18 respectively.
  • Q2 = sex- factor variable with 2 levels (female and male).
  • Q3 = grade- factor variable with 5 categories (9th grade, 10th grade, 11th grade, 12th grade, ungraded or other grade).The ungraded or other grade category is recoded as missing (NA).
  • Q13 = Weapon carrying to school in the past 30 days - factor variable with 5 levels (0 days, 1 day, 2 or 3 days, 4 or 5 days, 6 or more days).
  • Q23 = bullied on school property in the pas 30 days- factor variable with 2 levels (Yes, No).
  • Q66 = sexual orientation- factor variable with 4 categories (Heterosexual, Gay or Lesbian, Bisexual, and Not sure).

From our model above, those who were victims of bullying had 2.85 times greater odds of carrying weapons to school than those who were not bullied.This was statistically significant [OR= 2.85, CI: 2.24,3.61]. This model correctly predicted 97.55% of our observations. However, model sensitivty and specificity were low at 0 and 1 respectively. This may be due to the small number of observations with weapon carrying compared to the total observations in the dataset.

Test assumptions of Independence of observations and influence

Independence of observations The survey uses a 3-stage cluster sampling method to select students from a class to interview. It is likely that students in a class may be similar and so, observations may not be completely independent.

##Interpretation of model After adjusting for age, sex, grade and sexual identity, those who were bullied had 3.06 times greater odds of carrying weapons to school than those who were not bullied. This was statistically significant [OR= 3.06, CI: 2.38,3.91]. This model correctly predicted 97.55% of our observations. However, model sensitivity was low at 0.3%. This may be due to the small number of observations with weapon carrying compared to the total observations in the dataset. Model specificity was 99.99%- my model was better at predicting those who did not carry weapons than those who carried weapons. For every year increase in age between age 12 and 18 years, the odds of weapon carrying decreased by 22% after adjusting for victimization status, sex, grade, sexual identity. this was statistically significant (OR= 0.78, CI: 0.66- 0.92). The odds of carrying weapon was 3.36 times higher in males compared to the odds of weapon carrying in females after adjusting for victimization status, age, sex, grade, and sexual identity.this was statistically significant (OR= 3.36, CI: 2.58- 4.42). The odds of carrying weapon was 2.06 times higher in 10th graders compared to the odds of weapon carrying in 9th graders after adjusting for victimization status, age, sex, and sexual identity.this was statistically significant (OR= 2.06, CI: 1.41- 3.05). The odds of carrying weapon was 3.1 times higher in 11th graders compared to the odds of weapon carrying in 9th graders after adjusting for victimization status, age, sex, and sexual identity.this was statistically significant (OR= 3.1, CI: 1.92- 5.03). The odds of carrying weapon was 3.21 times higher in 12th graders compared to the odds of weapon carrying in 9th graders after adjusting for victimization status, age, sex, and sexual identity.this was statistically significant (OR= 3.21, CI: 1.72- 5.94). The odds of carrying weapon was 2.34 times higher in bisexuals compared to the odds of weapon carrying in heterosexuals after adjusting for victimization status, age, sex, and grade.this was statistically significant (OR= 2.34, CI: 1.60- 3.37). The odds of carrying weapon was 1.995 times higher in gays/lesbians compared to the odds of weapon carrying in heterosexuals after adjusting for victimization status, age, sex, and grade.this was statistically significant (OR= 1.995, CI: 1.08- 3.4). The odds of carrying weapon was 3.64 times higher in students questioning sexuality compared to the odds of weapon carrying in heterosexuals after adjusting for victimization status, age, sex, and grade.this was statistically significant (OR= 3.64, CI: 2.41- 5.34).
